               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350615-name-594" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-594" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-594" type="surname" value="LINDSEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-594" type="given" value="JOHN THOMAS"></interp>JOHN THOMAS LINDSEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a working jeweller, and live in Jewin<lb></lb>crescent, Jewin-street, Cripplegate. I have known the prisoner eighteen months—knowing he had a situation at Salters-hall chapel, I went to speak to him about his father—he had called on me once before, wishing me to make a ring for him—on the 16th of December, I received two notes from him, in consequence of which I sent three rings by his boy—he re<lb></lb>tained the property till the 23rd or 24th of December—I then received in<lb></lb>telligence, and went and left a note at his opposite neighbour's—I had not sold these rings; he had them on show—I afterwards understood they were pledged.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> If he had sent you the money you would have been satisfied? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did not know that I had sold them—I took him into custody on the 15th of this month—I sent him the price of the three rings—I had transactions with him before, but never received money.</p>
